{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631448"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:27:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:27:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17372"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17372"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10062"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70362"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10062","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10062"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17372"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55826"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5541"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23555"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23625"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70362","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70362"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe harm principle is a philosophical concept first described by John Stuart Mill that helps guide public health policy and interventions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the harm principle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The right of society to prevent individuals from harming themselves","The requirement to choose the least harmful of multiple options","The duty of healthcare workers to minimise patient harm","The principle that all harmful activities should be prohibited","The obligation to prevent harm to others while preserving individual liberty"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eobligation to prevent harm to others while preserving individual liberty\u003C/strong\u003E accurately describes the harm principle. This principle states that the only legitimate reason to interfere with individual freedom is to prevent harm to others. Personal choices that only affect oneself should not be restricted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eright of society to prevent individuals from harming themselves\u003C/strong\u003E describes paternalistic interference, which the harm principle explicitly rejects as it involves restricting personal choices that only affect the individual.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eduty of healthcare workers to minimise patient harm\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the principle of non-maleficence in medical ethics, which is distinct from the harm principle in public health.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Erequirement to choose the least harmful of multiple options\u003C/strong\u003E describes harm minimisation strategies, which is a separate concept from the harm principle.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eprinciple that all harmful activities should be prohibited\u003C/strong\u003E is overly broad and fails to distinguish between self-regarding actions and those that harm others.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe harm principle helps guide public health interventions by providing an ethical framework for when individual liberties can be restricted to protect population health, such as during infectious disease outbreaks.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The harm principle states that the only justification for interfering with individual liberty is to prevent harm to others.","Personal choices that only affect oneself should not be restricted by society according to the harm principle.","The harm principle is a key ethical framework in public health for balancing individual rights with population protection."],"references":["Folland A. The Harm Principle and the Nature of Harm. Utilitas. 2022;34(2):139-153. doi:10.1017/S0953820821000352"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55826"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17372"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55826","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55826"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-14T19:50:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-14T19:52:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10062"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70362"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"5326","lin